##########
To enhance the classification accuracy of the fall detection model, a transfer learning approach was adopted by replacing the original custom Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) with a pre-trained MobileNetV2 architecture.
MobileNetV2 was selected due to its lightweight structure and proven efficiency on embedded devices, aligning with the project's real-time and resource-constrained goals.
The base MobileNetV2 was used as a frozen feature extractor, with a custom classification head appended, consisting of a global average pooling layer, two dropout layers for regularisation, a dense ReLU-activated layer, and a final softmax output layer corresponding to the five activity classes (Fall, Idle, Lying, Pre-Fall, Sitting).
The model was trained using the Adam optimiser with a reduced learning rate, and class weights were computed dynamically to address the imbalance in the dataset.

Additionally, the data pipeline was improved by incorporating more aggressive data augmentation strategies, including random rotation, zoom, brightness variation, and flipping, to better generalise across unseen scenarios.
Training was extended to 50 epochs with early stopping enabled, and the evaluation pipeline saved comprehensive results, including confusion matrices and training curves, for analysis.
Following these changes, the final MobileNetV2-based model achieved a test accuracy of 90.13% and a weighted F1-score of 91%, demonstrating a significant performance improvement over the initial custom CNN approach.
